   <abstract >This study investigated the allocation of Title I funds by elementary school principals in the Alabama Russell County School District. The following research questions were explored: How do Russell County elementary school principals design an effective Title I allocation system? What type(s) of decision-making guide Russell County elementary school principals in designing an effective Title I allocation system? Purposive and convenience sampling was used for the selection of study participants. Participants consisted of four elementary school principals from Russell County School District. Semi-structured interviews were conducted to gather data addressing the research questions. Through descriptive coding, categorical data analysis, and subcoding, the study examined how four elementary school principals designed an effective allocation system. The Region 9 Comprehensive Center (2024) presents equity, transparency, engagement of stakeholders, and alignment with district goals and priorities as the four properties of their framework for an effective resource allocation system. The findings highlight Russell County's resource allocation system is procedural, providing sequential steps to resource allocation: 1. Identify needs. 2. Determine how to address the needs. 3. Align resources and initiatives with funding. 4. Engage stakeholders. Although the two systems differ in structure, elements of the Region 9 framework are found within the steps of Russell County's allocation system. Another consideration of this study was, what type(s) of decision-making process are involved in allocating resources. This study found that principals made rational choices due to limitations in resources and their perceptions of what would yield the best educational outcomes. In addition to making rational decisions, principals used data-based decision-making to guide their decisions around the needs of their schools and how to address them.</abstract>
